<h1>@HI{{wo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{ha}} ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates the direct object of a transitive verb.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates the direct object of a passive verb.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates the person made to do something in a causative sentence.
</p>

<p>
With @HI{{suru}}, <strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates a specific occupation or position.
</p>

<p>
With @HI{{tai}} or @HI{{tagaru}}, <strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates a wish or a desire.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates a movement from a smaller place to a larger one, both physically and in an abstract sense.
</p>

<p>
When used with a verb of motion, <strong>@HI{{wo}}</strong> indicates the location of the movement rather than the destination.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{evening}}beha @KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}<strong>wo</strong> @KJ{{see}}ta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I saw a film yesterday evening.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
